~ Abstract
INTRO TO BUILDING Designed at a time when fire zone models and nodal evacuation simulations were on the forefront of fire engineering design, Te Papa Tongarewa, Museum of New Zealand stretched the boundaries of performance based fire engineering. The result was a heavily engineered approach to fire safety with a complex array of fire safety systems.
This paper outlines the case study of a reassessment of the museum using computation fluid dynamics (CFD) and agent based evacuation modeling. Whilst these tools add a level of complexity to fire modeling which is always justifiable, the enable engineers to better understand the impacts of fire and smoke on the building. Coupled with a more comprehensive regulatory environment, these CFD modeling and agent based evacuation simulations have helped to improve life safety and asset protection in Te Papa museum in a cost effective manner. 
~

