As mentioned above, the FDS model fails to take account of air introduced to the building by the escape route pressurization system. If for example half of the peak makeup air volume, 30 m^3^s^-1^, can be relied upon to discharge into the atrium firecell, this would reduce the required makeup air area from 100 m^3^s^-1^ to 70 m^3^s^-1^.  The corresponding 30% reduction makeup air velocity to about 3.5 ms^-1^ is could reduce the fire plume disturbance. Nevertheless, reconfiguring the makeup air system and reducing the makeup air velocity to approximately 1 ms^-1^ has been shown to improve the efficiency of the smoke control system, making the difference between passing and failing NZBC acceptance criteria. 

##Function space fire
The Icon function center is located on Level 2 of the museum. Of interest is that there is that the function center forms part of a makeup air path, with an actuated vent which opens on activation of the Entrance Atrium smoke extract system. It is separated from the remainder of the atrium firecell by a glass partition and doors which are commonly held open. 

For the purpose of the fire engineering design of the building, it would have been designed to comply with the Acceptable Solution document C2/AS1, with two escape routes and automatic sprinkler coverage. In the reassessment, the a fire was modeled in Icon function space to see what impact a fire on a makeup air path would have on the building. An FDS simulation showed that in the event of  fire in the function space, smoke would  into the entrance atrium and activates multiple extract systems. These will then then draw makeup air through the function space and room of fire origin, spreading smoke throughout the museum, as shown in Figure [#fig-extentofsmokespread]. Whilst this fire is unlikely to result in untenable conditions, it has the potential to cause smoke damage to large areas of the museum. Having identified the risk, relatively easy options are being investigated to isolate the effects of a fire in the function space, such as providing smoke sealed, self closing doors between the function space and atriums. 

